108
00:03:38,330 --> 00:03:39,940
Right, so now you've got your free stock

109
00:03:39,940 --> 00:03:41,850
and you're ready to invest into some more,

110
00:03:41,850 --> 00:03:43,050
but where should you start?

111
00:03:43,050 --> 00:03:44,360
Well, if you're anything like me,

112
00:03:44,360 --> 00:03:46,440
it makes sense to start with the numbers.

113
00:03:46,440 --> 00:03:48,960
We call this quantitative analysis.

114
00:03:48,960 --> 00:03:51,710
Whenever I'm thinking about
investing in a company

115
00:03:51,710 --> 00:03:54,260
I make sure to look at
all these figures first.

116
00:03:54,260 --> 00:03:56,370
If the financials don't look good to me,

117
00:03:56,370 --> 00:03:57,330
then it's very rare

118
00:03:57,330 --> 00:03:59,800
that I'll do any further
research into the company.

119
00:03:59,800 --> 00:04:00,730
It's kind of like when you

120
00:04:00,730 --> 00:04:03,730
go on a first date with someone
and they seem really nice,

121
00:04:03,730 --> 00:04:05,730
however, it isn't until you really start

122
00:04:05,730 --> 00:04:07,890
getting to know all the details about them

123
00:04:07,890 --> 00:04:10,030
that you might start
to notice their flaws,

124
00:04:10,030 --> 00:04:12,950
like eating with their mouth
open or picking their nose.

125
00:04:12,950 --> 00:04:16,040
If only they gave you a
non-biased comprehensive list

126
00:04:16,040 --> 00:04:17,350
of how they actually are

127
00:04:17,350 --> 00:04:19,320
so you can make an educated decision

128
00:04:19,320 --> 00:04:21,040
whether you want to date them or not.

129
00:04:21,040 --> 00:04:22,730
I don't have a solution to this problem,

130
00:04:22,730 --> 00:04:25,210
but luckily that's
exactly what companies do.

131
00:04:25,210 --> 00:04:26,130
It's brilliant.

132
00:04:26,130 --> 00:04:27,680
You can find out this information

133
00:04:27,680 --> 00:04:29,550
for free on Yahoo! Finance,

134
00:04:29,550 --> 00:04:31,190
which is the website that I use.

135
00:04:31,190 --> 00:04:33,510
There are three main
aspects that I look at.

136
00:04:33,510 --> 00:04:35,670
First, let's break down the balance sheet.

137
00:04:35,670 --> 00:04:38,240
I know it doesn't sound too
interesting, but trust me,

138
00:04:38,240 --> 00:04:41,470
this is where you find some
of the real juicy information.

139
00:04:41,470 --> 00:04:43,960
The whole purpose of this
sheet is in the name:

140
00:04:43,960 --> 00:04:46,710
to balance assets and liabilities.

141
00:04:46,710 --> 00:04:48,270
Think of it a bit like this.

142
00:04:48,270 --> 00:04:50,760
You may own a watch or rental property,

143
00:04:50,760 --> 00:04:52,230
and these are your assets,

144
00:04:52,230 --> 00:04:54,900
but let's say you have
loads of credit card debt.

145
00:04:54,900 --> 00:04:56,660
This is one of your liabilities,

146
00:04:56,660 --> 00:04:59,430
so let's break down some
of the gobbledy-goop terms

147
00:04:59,430 --> 00:05:02,610
so you can easily understand
this complicated-looking sheet

148
00:05:02,610 --> 00:05:03,890
and impress your friends.

149
00:05:03,890 --> 00:05:06,450
Assets are broken down
into three categories.

150
00:05:06,450 --> 00:05:08,300
Current assets are things
that could be turned

151
00:05:08,300 --> 00:05:10,120
into cash within 12 months.

152
00:05:10,120 --> 00:05:11,170
Longer-term assets

153
00:05:11,170 --> 00:05:12,700
are things like their headquarters

154
00:05:12,700 --> 00:05:14,480
which they usually don't sell in a hurry.

155
00:05:14,480 --> 00:05:16,280
Companies can also have assets

156
00:05:16,280 --> 00:05:17,870
that you can't physically touch

157
00:05:17,870 --> 00:05:20,080
known as non-tangible assets,

158
00:05:20,080 --> 00:05:21,790
such as the brand recognition

159
00:05:21,790 --> 00:05:23,450
of an established business

160
00:05:23,450 --> 00:05:25,700
that has been trusted for generations.

161
00:05:25,700 --> 00:05:27,370
I like to think of Coca-Cola.

162
00:05:27,370 --> 00:05:29,160
And then we come to the liabilities,

163
00:05:29,160 --> 00:05:30,900
and what I'm really interested in here

164
00:05:30,900 --> 00:05:32,610
are the current liabilities

165
00:05:32,610 --> 00:05:33,790
as this is the debt that they'll

166
00:05:33,790 --> 00:05:35,610
need to repay within 12 months.

167
00:05:35,610 --> 00:05:37,400
With this, there is a simple calculation

168
00:05:37,400 --> 00:05:39,450
you can do to easily know if the company

169
00:05:39,450 --> 00:05:40,700
is high-risk or not,

170
00:05:40,700 --> 00:05:43,310
and that is total current assets divided

171
00:05:43,310 --> 00:05:45,260
by total current liabilities.

172
00:05:45,260 --> 00:05:46,540
A good rule of thumb here

173
00:05:46,540 --> 00:05:48,280
is the numbers should be above one,

174
00:05:48,280 --> 00:05:50,030
but how does this work in practice?

175
00:05:50,030 --> 00:05:52,230
Let's take Apple's balance
sheet, for example.

176
00:05:52,230 --> 00:05:54,240
Apple's total current assets

177
00:05:54,240 --> 00:05:57,120
divided by their total current liability

178
00:05:57,120 --> 00:05:59,690
comes to 1.4 when rounded up.

179
00:05:59,690 --> 00:06:01,620
This is great as now we know that Apple

180
00:06:01,620 --> 00:06:03,970
are able to pay off all
their short-term debt

181
00:06:03,970 --> 00:06:05,560
nearly 1-1/2 times.

182
00:06:05,560 --> 00:06:08,180
The second document is really
important to have a look at

183
00:06:08,180 --> 00:06:09,550
is the income statement.

184
00:06:09,550 --> 00:06:12,650
If you've ever heard the saying
of the top and bottom line,

185
00:06:12,650 --> 00:06:13,920
this is where it comes from.

186
00:06:13,920 --> 00:06:15,430
At the top of the statement,

187
00:06:15,430 --> 00:06:17,110
this is the total revenue,

188
00:06:17,110 --> 00:06:19,430
which is the total the business take,

189
00:06:19,430 --> 00:06:21,800
and at the bottom is the net income,

190
00:06:21,800 --> 00:06:23,470
which is the money that the company makes

191
00:06:23,470 --> 00:06:26,050
after all the expenses have been deducted.

192
00:06:26,050 --> 00:06:28,240
Every business has these expenses,

193
00:06:28,240 --> 00:06:30,950
the cost of operation
and the cost of revenue.

194
00:06:30,950 --> 00:06:34,060
So, let's take a simple business
like a smoothie company.

195
00:06:34,060 --> 00:06:35,730
Their cost of revenue is fruit.

196
00:06:35,730 --> 00:06:37,970
They can't make their
smoothies without buying that.

197
00:06:37,970 --> 00:06:41,000
Therefore, that is a cost
they have no choice about.

198
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:43,130
It's a simple fact of
running their business,

199
00:06:43,130 --> 00:06:45,280
but the next thing they
do have a choice about,

200
00:06:45,280 --> 00:06:47,410
which is their operating expenses:

201
00:06:47,410 --> 00:06:48,640
who they're hiring

202
00:06:48,640 --> 00:06:50,560
and what kind of wages
that they're paying them.

203
00:06:50,560 --> 00:06:52,410
After these expenses are deducted

204
00:06:52,410 --> 00:06:53,750
from the total amount of money

205
00:06:53,750 --> 00:06:55,260
they take for their customers,

206
00:06:55,260 --> 00:06:57,250
you get the operating income.

207
00:06:57,250 --> 00:06:59,010
So, here's my simple calculation

208
00:06:59,010 --> 00:07:01,510
that lets me know if
the business is healthy:

209
00:07:01,510 --> 00:07:05,840
operating income divided
by total revenue times 100.

210
00:07:05,840 --> 00:07:08,510
Ideally, I look for above 15%.

211
00:07:08,510 --> 00:07:09,730
Using Apple again,

212
00:07:09,730 --> 00:07:13,440
let's take this number
divided by this number,

213
00:07:13,440 --> 00:07:16,330
and we get 27%, which is great.

214
00:07:16,330 --> 00:07:19,580
The last one of the big three
is the statement of cashflow.

215
00:07:19,580 --> 00:07:21,800
I'm not going to spend
too much time on this one

216
00:07:21,800 --> 00:07:23,000
as when you boil it down,

217
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:24,120
it's pretty simple.

218
00:07:24,120 --> 00:07:25,410
The main thing I look out for

219
00:07:25,410 --> 00:07:27,010
is if the company I'm investing in

220
00:07:27,010 --> 00:07:30,130
has increased in free
cashflow year on year,

221
00:07:30,130 --> 00:07:31,770
which is money they can use

222
00:07:31,770 --> 00:07:34,500
to reinvest all payback to investors.

223
00:07:34,500 --> 00:07:36,300
A big red flag here is sometimes

224
00:07:36,300 --> 00:07:38,200
I see the cash flow is negative

225
00:07:38,200 --> 00:07:40,210
but the company's still paying dividends

226
00:07:40,210 --> 00:07:41,600
back to its investors.

227
00:07:41,600 --> 00:07:43,290
It's just unsustainable,

228
00:07:43,290 --> 00:07:44,490
and eventually the business

229
00:07:44,490 --> 00:07:46,110
is just going to run out of cash.

230
00:07:46,110 --> 00:07:48,580
Now, once I've had a good
look at all these numbers,

231
00:07:48,580 --> 00:07:50,420
it's time to get into the juicy stuff,

232
00:07:50,420 --> 00:07:53,280
and that's all about analyzing
the qualities of a company.

233
00:07:53,280 --> 00:07:55,710
This is known as qualitative analysis.

234
00:07:55,710 --> 00:07:58,660
One of the qualities I look
for is brand recognition.

235
00:07:58,660 --> 00:08:00,300
When I say the word Apple,

236
00:08:00,300 --> 00:08:03,380
most people think about the
company rather than the fruit.

237
00:08:03,380 --> 00:08:04,670
I know I keep referring to it,

238
00:08:04,670 --> 00:08:06,140
but it's a great example

239
00:08:06,140 --> 00:08:07,770
of amazing brand recognition

240
00:08:07,770 --> 00:08:09,660
that won't be going away anytime soon.

241
00:08:09,660 --> 00:08:10,870
Being a household brand name

242
00:08:10,870 --> 00:08:12,500
comes with a lot of consumer trust,

243
00:08:12,500 --> 00:08:14,410
so when they launch a new product,

244
00:08:14,410 --> 00:08:16,260
people are much more likely to try it out,

245
00:08:16,260 --> 00:08:18,970
especially if it's something
unique or groundbreaking,

246
00:08:18,970 --> 00:08:20,280
such as the iPad.

247
00:08:20,280 --> 00:08:24,220
- And we'd like to show it to
you today for the first time,

248
00:08:24,220 --> 00:08:26,958
and we call it the iPad.

249
00:08:26,958 --> 00:08:30,250
(audience cheering)

250
00:08:30,250 --> 00:08:32,740
- This helps companies
like Apple shape our future

251
00:08:32,740 --> 00:08:35,530
and create entire new
markets and revenue streams.

252
00:08:35,530 --> 00:08:38,810
Another great example of
brand awareness is Coca-Cola.

253
00:08:38,810 --> 00:08:41,090
It's the second-most recognized word

254
00:08:41,090 --> 00:08:42,760
in the world after okay.

255
00:08:42,760 --> 00:08:43,593
- Mm-kay.

256
00:08:43,593 --> 00:08:46,370
- Something that really affects
price movements is the news.

257
00:08:46,370 --> 00:08:47,530
I always keep an eye on it,

258
00:08:47,530 --> 00:08:50,300
and in particular rumors on social media.

259
00:08:50,300 --> 00:08:52,970
You may have heard about
the whole GameStop situation

260
00:08:52,970 --> 00:08:55,100
where a small bunch of retail investors

261
00:08:55,100 --> 00:08:57,710
managed to outsmart the top hedge funds

262
00:08:57,710 --> 00:08:59,740
by finding a flaw in their strategy.

263
00:08:59,740 --> 00:09:01,535
They were able to use
this to their advantage

264
00:09:01,535 --> 00:09:02,850
and earn a lot of money.

265
00:09:02,850 --> 00:09:05,830
- [Anchor] Tonight, it's Wall
Street's David versus Goliath.

266
00:09:05,830 --> 00:09:08,380
The struggling video
game retailer GameStop

267
00:09:08,380 --> 00:09:11,700
skyrocketing about 8000% over six months.

268
00:09:11,700 --> 00:09:13,070
- But once the news broke

269
00:09:13,070 --> 00:09:15,910
and more people started to
jump onto the bandwagon,

270
00:09:15,910 --> 00:09:17,870
the big profits had already been made.

271
00:09:17,870 --> 00:09:20,607
This is a great example
of the age-old saying,

272
00:09:20,607 --> 00:09:22,650
"buy the rumor, sell the news."

273
00:09:22,650 --> 00:09:23,960
I learned this valuable lesson

274
00:09:23,960 --> 00:09:26,200
during the dot-com boom in the '90s.

275
00:09:26,200 --> 00:09:27,590
When I started investing,

276
00:09:27,590 --> 00:09:29,820
people were amazed that
I was pouring money

277
00:09:29,820 --> 00:09:33,740
into companies whose main
asset was a .com domain name.

278
00:09:33,740 --> 00:09:35,290
However, within six months,

279
00:09:35,290 --> 00:09:36,890
it seemed that everyone's telling me

280
00:09:36,890 --> 00:09:39,330
that they were buying
shares in.com companies,

281
00:09:39,330 --> 00:09:40,660
even my hair dresser.

282
00:09:40,660 --> 00:09:42,380
I decided to start selling

283
00:09:42,380 --> 00:09:45,690
to buy more real estate just
weeks before the bubble burst,

284
00:09:45,690 --> 00:09:48,380
and I managed to save the
majority of my profits.

285
00:09:48,380 --> 00:09:49,570
Others weren't so lucky.

286
00:09:49,570 --> 00:09:52,280
Everyone thought that internet
businesses were the future,

287
00:09:52,280 --> 00:09:53,500
and they were eventually right,

288
00:09:53,500 --> 00:09:56,490
however, most of the original
companies never recovered,

289
00:09:56,490 --> 00:09:58,620
and I saw some of my friends make millions

290
00:09:58,620 --> 00:10:01,090
just to lose 90% of their investment

291
00:10:01,090 --> 00:10:02,210
when everything crashed.

292
00:10:02,210 --> 00:10:04,820
Only a handful of companies
managed to weather the storm,

293
00:10:04,820 --> 00:10:05,700
such as Amazon.

294
00:10:05,700 --> 00:10:08,120
This showed me that the
hype generated by the news

295
00:10:08,120 --> 00:10:09,530
and other people talking about it

296
00:10:09,530 --> 00:10:11,040
really just caused the prices

297
00:10:11,040 --> 00:10:13,690
to get out of control
and become unsustainable.

298
00:10:13,690 --> 00:10:15,260
So, whenever I feel like hype

299
00:10:15,260 --> 00:10:17,320
is driving the price
of a particular stock,

300
00:10:17,320 --> 00:10:20,340
I know that it probably isn't
a great long-term investment.

301
00:10:20,340 --> 00:10:21,970
Although, with the dot-com bubble,

302
00:10:21,970 --> 00:10:25,090
it is true that a lot of
companies did rebound eventually.

303
00:10:25,090 --> 00:10:27,800
The next important factor is
the leadership of the company,

304
00:10:27,800 --> 00:10:30,040
even more so nowadays with social media,

305
00:10:30,040 --> 00:10:32,410
and what the leaders say
is having a huge effect

306
00:10:32,410 --> 00:10:33,540
on the price of the stock.

307
00:10:33,540 --> 00:10:35,700
A prime example of this is Elon Musk,

308
00:10:35,700 --> 00:10:37,670
who is very clearly the visionary

309
00:10:37,670 --> 00:10:39,330
behind all of his companies,

310
00:10:39,330 --> 00:10:40,940
one of them, of course, being Tesla.

311
00:10:40,940 --> 00:10:42,470
Just imagine if Elon Musk

312
00:10:42,470 --> 00:10:44,780
decided he was bored
of making electric cars

313
00:10:44,780 --> 00:10:47,360
and tweeted that he were
standing down from Tesla

314
00:10:47,360 --> 00:10:51,040
to focus on SpaceX and his
mission to colonize Mars.

315
00:10:51,040 --> 00:10:52,890
I think this reliance on Elon Musk

316
00:10:52,890 --> 00:10:54,910
is one of Tesla's greatest strengths,

317
00:10:54,910 --> 00:10:57,440
but also one of its greatest weaknesses,

318
00:10:57,440 --> 00:11:00,140
as the company is highly
affected by his actions.

319
00:11:00,140 --> 00:11:01,610
This brings me to my next point,

320
00:11:01,610 --> 00:11:04,350
which is to look out for
emerging future industries

321
00:11:04,350 --> 00:11:06,230
like electric vehicle technology,

322
00:11:06,230 --> 00:11:08,110
which Tesla is leading the way in.

323
00:11:08,110 --> 00:11:11,280
These types of investments
are really your growth stocks.

324
00:11:11,280 --> 00:11:14,070
My friend, Simon Squibb
often tells me he believes

325
00:11:14,070 --> 00:11:15,240
that in the future,

326
00:11:15,240 --> 00:11:18,030
doctors will be replaced
by artificial intelligence.

327
00:11:18,030 --> 00:11:20,010
This sounds like the
stuff of science fiction,

328
00:11:20,010 --> 00:11:21,790
however, when I was younger,

329
00:11:21,790 --> 00:11:24,530
this was what I used to see on Star Trek.

330
00:11:24,530 --> 00:11:26,050
- Spock.

331
00:11:26,050 --> 00:11:27,070
- [Spock] Spock here.

332
00:11:27,070 --> 00:11:28,920
- In fact, this is even better.

333
00:11:28,920 --> 00:11:30,520
I actually first heard of Tesla

334
00:11:30,520 --> 00:11:33,070
when it was featured
on "Top Gear" in 2008.

335
00:11:33,070 --> 00:11:34,800
It wasn't a very flattering review

336
00:11:34,800 --> 00:11:37,670
as they showed the car running
out of batteries in 50 miles,

337
00:11:37,670 --> 00:11:40,300
which was only a quarter
of the advertised range.

338
00:11:40,300 --> 00:11:41,900
Elon wasn't very happy about this

339
00:11:41,900 --> 00:11:44,690
and he actually later filed
a lawsuit against the show.

340
00:11:44,690 --> 00:11:47,430
However, the segment
certainly piqued my interest

341
00:11:47,430 --> 00:11:49,130
and I could see they were onto something.

342
00:11:49,130 --> 00:11:50,340
During my time investing,

343
00:11:50,340 --> 00:11:52,360
I've seen a huge shift in each sector.

344
00:11:52,360 --> 00:11:54,440
- Oh, it's the American on Sectorus.

345
00:11:54,440 --> 00:11:56,530
- Let me take you back
to when I was younger,

346
00:11:56,530 --> 00:11:58,100
if you can imagine that far back.

347
00:11:58,100 --> 00:11:59,940
I remember sitting at my grandma's house

348
00:11:59,940 --> 00:12:01,440
and watching this guy come along

349
00:12:01,440 --> 00:12:03,360
with a sack of coal on his back,

350
00:12:03,360 --> 00:12:05,070
which he would deliver to my grandma

351
00:12:05,070 --> 00:12:06,560
so she could heat her house.

352
00:12:06,560 --> 00:12:10,310
Nowadays, most people use
gas, so no more Mr. Coal Man,

353
00:12:10,310 --> 00:12:12,750
and this sector is all set to change again

354
00:12:12,750 --> 00:12:15,240
with the introduction of
renewable electricity.

355
00:12:15,240 --> 00:12:16,850
But that's three major shifts

356
00:12:16,850 --> 00:12:18,770
that I'll experience in my lifetime.

357
00:12:18,770 --> 00:12:20,230
If I'd been stuck in my ways

358
00:12:20,230 --> 00:12:22,250
and not taking notes to these changes,

359
00:12:22,250 --> 00:12:24,470
then my investments would
have been left in the past,

360
00:12:24,470 --> 00:12:25,900
just like the coal industry.

361
00:12:25,900 --> 00:12:27,760
So, before investing in a stock,

362
00:12:27,760 --> 00:12:30,760
I always think about whether
a future shift in sector

363
00:12:30,760 --> 00:12:34,160
will have a positive or
negative impact on that company.

364
00:12:34,160 --> 00:12:36,557
But how do I predict when
the best time to buy is?

365
00:12:36,557 --> 00:12:37,390
You don't,

366
00:12:37,390 --> 00:12:39,820
but there's a strategy I
use to get around this,

367
00:12:39,820 --> 00:12:42,010
and it's called dollar cost averaging.

368
00:12:42,010 --> 00:12:44,007
Let's imagine you were
to invest once a month

369
00:12:44,007 --> 00:12:45,280
for three months.

370
00:12:45,280 --> 00:12:48,040
Month One, the stock might cost you $200,

371
00:12:48,040 --> 00:12:49,717
Month Two, $150,

372
00:12:49,717 --> 00:12:51,980
and Month Three, $130.

373
00:12:51,980 --> 00:12:54,860
Of course, if you knew it
was going to dip to $130,

374
00:12:54,860 --> 00:12:55,920
you'd have bought then,

375
00:12:55,920 --> 00:12:58,730
however no one knows how
low the price will go.

376
00:12:58,730 --> 00:12:59,563
But by doing this,

377
00:12:59,563 --> 00:13:01,880
instead of investing all
your money in Month One

378
00:13:01,880 --> 00:13:03,890
when your stock was at $200,

379
00:13:03,890 --> 00:13:07,213
you actually lower your
average buying price to $160.

380
00:13:07,213 --> 00:13:09,870
This is also known as buying the dip.

381
00:13:09,870 --> 00:13:11,720
Instead of getting scared and selling

382
00:13:11,720 --> 00:13:13,530
like the majority of people would,

383
00:13:13,530 --> 00:13:15,090
the idea is to buy more,

384
00:13:15,090 --> 00:13:17,230
because it's like having a garage sale,

385
00:13:17,230 --> 00:13:18,860
and if you've done all your research

386
00:13:18,860 --> 00:13:20,320
and you like the company,

387
00:13:20,320 --> 00:13:22,500
then the stock is at a bargain price.

388
00:13:22,500 --> 00:13:24,490
So, I'm going to leave the
next video right up there,

389
00:13:24,490 --> 00:13:26,110
but don't click on it just yet.

390
